ctually used and is amortized over the entire sync (a single endpoint setup, not per-request).\n\n### Server round-trips\n\n**Private-repo cold-start** now costs an extra HTTP round-trip per endpoint (anon GET → 401 → authed GET → 200) instead of one (authed GET → 200). At git-sync's scale (one sync = one pair of endpoints, runs periodically, not per-PR), this is **immaterial**. `info/refs` is small; the extra round-trip is dwarfed by pack negotiation and transfer. Note: `c.Auth` is cached at line 221 so subsequent `PostRPC` calls on the same conn skip the round-trip — only the first `/info/refs` pays it.\n\n### Memory / credential lifetime\n\n`basicAuth` struct (`internal/gitproto/smarthttp.go:644`) holds `username`/`password` as plain Go strings on the `HTTPConn`. They live until the conn is GC'd, never zeroed. Same is true for `transporthttp.BasicAuth` from explicit auth — **no regression**, just matches existing behaviour. Worth a future hardening pass (e.g. wipe-on-conn-close), but **acceptable for this PR**.\n\n### Other observations\n\n- `internal/syncer/syncer.go:383` attaches `GitCredentialHelper{}` to every HTTPConn where `authMethod == nil`. The helper is a zero-size struct, so no allocation cost. Good.\n- `internal/auth/auth.go:68` builds `cmd.Env = append(os.Environ(), \"GIT_TERMINAL_PROMPT=0\")` on **every** invocation of `newGitCredentialCmd` (fill/approve/reject). `os.Environ()` allocates a fresh slice each call. At most 2 calls per sync, so trivially small — **not worth optimizing**.\n- `doInfoRefsRequest` is only called from `RequestInfoRefs` (one or two times per sync); no concern about it being on a per-pack-line path.\n\n### Findings summary\n\n| # | Location | Severity | Verdict |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | `smarthttp.go:187-225` happy-path overhead | none | acceptable; small win |\n| 2 | `smarthttp.go:199,203,207,227` body lifecycle | none | all paths close correctly |\n| 3 | subprocess count delta | mixed | net win for scripted/anon, +1 for 40